<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-circumscribed-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Circumscribed Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Construct an inscribed, circumscribed and escribed circles on a triangle</li>
                              <li>Determine the centroid and orthocentre of a triangle</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover the circumcenter by asking: <q>can you draw a circle that passes through all three vertices of a triangle?</q>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Let learners attempt part (a) with trial and error — most will not find the right centre immediately, and that frustration motivates the reasoning in part (c). 
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>A Circle Through All Three Vertices</title>
                <p>
                    In this activity you will investigate whether a circle can pass through all three vertices of a triangle, and how to find its centre.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a triangle <m>ABC</m> of your choice using a ruler. Using a compass, try to draw a circle that passes exactly through all three vertices. Mark the centre <m>O</m> you used. (You may need several attempts!)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare with a classmate. Did you choose the same centre? Whose circle passes more accurately through all three vertices?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Reason about where the centre must be. The circle passes through <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, so the centre is equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. What is the set of all points equidistant from two given points? Where must the centre also lie because the circle passes through <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    The set of points equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>. Similarly for <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>. The centre lies on both perpendicular bisectors, so it must be their intersection.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the circumcenter construction by introducing key terminology.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    For a triangle <m>\triangle ABC</m>, the <term>circumcircle</term> is the unique circle that goes through <m>A,B,\text{ and }C</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>circumcenter</term> <m>O</m> is the centre of the circumcircle, and is equidistant from the three vertices: <m>OA = OB = OC</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The radius of the circumcircle is called the <term>circumradius</term>, denoted <m>R</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        
        <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-intro">
        <caption>The circumcircle of triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
        <image width="65%">
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                    %% --- SET ---
                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 2.5/4/C}

                    %% --- CALCULATE ---
                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                    \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                    \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                    \tkzDefMidPoint(A,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MAC}

                    %% --- DRAW ---
                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                    \tkzDrawSegments[red!60!black](O,A O,B O,C)
                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,A O,B O,C)

                    %% --- LABEL ---
                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                    \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                    \tkzLabelSegment[sloped, above](O,A){$R$}
                    \tkzLabelSegment[above left](A,C){$b$}
                    \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$a$}
                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$c$}

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
        </figure>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Constructing the Circumscribed Circle</title>
        <p>
            To construct the circumscribed circle of a triangle using only a pair of compasses and a straightedge, follow these steps. The idea is that the centre must be equidistant from all three vertices, so it lies on the perpendicular bisector of every side.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Draw the triangle <m>ABC</m> accurately with a ruler.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-con-step1">
                    <caption>Step 1: the triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Construct the perpendicular bisector of side <m>AB</m>. Open your compasses to more than half of <m>AB</m>. With the point at <m>A</m>, draw a short arc above and below <m>AB</m>; without changing the width, draw two matching arcs from <m>B</m>. The arcs cross at two points, and the straight line through these points is the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m> — every point on it is equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-con-step2">
                    <caption>Step 2: equal arcs from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> give the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m> (red).</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cAB}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](A)\tkzGetPoint{cBA}
                                \tkzInterCC(A,cAB)(B,cBA)\tkzGetPoints{P1}{P2}
                                \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mab}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzCompass[red](A,P1)\tkzCompass[red](A,P2)
                                \tkzCompass[red](B,P1)\tkzCompass[red](B,P2)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.25, red, thick](P1,P2)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](A,Mab,P1)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    In exactly the same way, construct the perpendicular bisector of a second side, <m>BC</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-con-step3">
                    <caption>Step 3: the perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m> (blue), built the same way.</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cAB}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](A)\tkzGetPoint{cBA}
                                \tkzInterCC(A,cAB)(B,cBA)\tkzGetPoints{P1}{P2}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](C)\tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center C ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cCB}
                                \tkzInterCC(B,cBC)(C,cCB)\tkzGetPoints{Q1}{Q2}
                                \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Mbc}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.25, red!45, thin](P1,P2)
                                \tkzCompass[blue](B,Q1)\tkzCompass[blue](B,Q2)
                                \tkzCompass[blue](C,Q1)\tkzCompass[blue](C,Q2)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.25, blue, thick](Q1,Q2)
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](C,Mbc,Q1)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The two perpendicular bisectors meet at a single point <m>O</m>, the <term>circumcenter</term>. Because <m>O</m> lies on the bisector of <m>AB</m> it is equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>; because it lies on the bisector of <m>BC</m> it is equidistant from <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>. Therefore <m>OA = OB = OC</m> (shown dotted).
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-con-step4">
                    <caption>Step 4: the perpendicular bisectors meet at the circumcenter <m>O</m>, with <m>OA = OB = OC</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cAB}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](A)\tkzGetPoint{cBA}
                                \tkzInterCC(A,cAB)(B,cBA)\tkzGetPoints{P1}{P2}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](C)\tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center C ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cCB}
                                \tkzInterCC(B,cBC)(C,cCB)\tkzGetPoints{Q1}{Q2}
                                \tkzInterLL(P1,P2)(Q1,Q2)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.25, red!55, thin](P1,P2)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.25, blue!55, thin](Q1,Q2)
                                \tkzDrawSegments[densely dotted, gray](O,A O,B O,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoint[size=3.5pt](O)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Set your compasses to the distance <m>OA</m> and, with the point at <m>O</m>, draw the circle. This <term>circumscribed circle</term> passes through all three vertices; its radius is the circumradius <m>R</m>. As a check, the perpendicular bisector of the third side, <m>CA</m>, passes through <m>O</m> too.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-con-step5">
                    <caption>Step 5: the circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>R = OA</m> is the circumscribed circle.</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/4/A}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center A ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cAB}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](A)\tkzGetPoint{cBA}
                                \tkzInterCC(A,cAB)(B,cBA)\tkzGetPoints{P1}{P2}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 0.7](C)\tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center C ratio 0.7](B)\tkzGetPoint{cCB}
                                \tkzInterCC(B,cBC)(C,cCB)\tkzGetPoints{Q1}{Q2}
                                \tkzInterLL(P1,P2)(Q1,Q2)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.1 and 0.1, red!35, thin](P1,P2)
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.1 and 0.1, blue!35, thin](Q1,Q2)
                                \tkzDrawCircle[teal, thick](O,A)
                                \tkzDrawSegment[densely dotted, gray](O,A)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped](O,A){$R$}
                                \tkzDrawSegment(A,O)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoint[size=3.5pt](O)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below right](O){$O$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="exploration-circumscribed-construction">
        <title>Interactive Construction of the Circumscribed Circle</title>
        <p>
            Step through the construction with the <em>Next</em> and <em>Back</em> buttons, and drag the vertices <m>A</m>, <m>B</m> and <m>C</m> to see how the perpendicular bisectors, the circumcenter <m>O</m> and the circumscribed circle adapt.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="figure-circumscribed-construction">
        <caption>Constructing the circumscribed circle of a triangle</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-circumscribed" platform="jsxgraph"
                        aspect="8:6.5" source="jsxgraph/circumscribed-circle-construction.js" width="80%">
                <sbsgroup>
                    <sidebyside width="85%" margins="1%">
                        <slate xml:id="box_circum" surface="jsxboard" aspect="5:4"/>
                    </sidebyside>
                    <sidebyside width="85%" margins="1%">
                        <slate surface="html">
                            <div id="caption_circum"
                                style="font:15px/1.45 system-ui,Segoe UI,Arial,sans-serif;color:#222;text-align:center;min-height:60px;"
                                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"></div>
                        </slate>
                    </sidebyside>
                    <sidebyside widths="30% 30%" margins="20%">
                        <slate surface="html">
                            <input id="back_circum" type="button" value="◀ Back"
                                onkeypress="circumBack();" onclick="circumBack();"
                                style="font-size:16px; width:100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"/>
                        </slate>
                        <slate surface="html">
                            <input id="next_circum" type="button" value="Next ▶"
                                onkeypress="circumNext();" onclick="circumNext();"
                                style="font-size:16px; width:100%; height:30px;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"/>
                        </slate>
                    </sidebyside>
                </sbsgroup>
                <instructions>
                    <p>Use <em>Next</em> and <em>Back</em> to step through the construction. Drag the vertices A, B and C at any time — the whole construction stays correct.</p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-circumscribed-circle">
        <title>The Circumcircle and Circumradius</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose <m>\triangle ABC</m> has side lengths <m>a = BC</m>, <m>b = AC</m>, and <m>c = AB</m>.
                <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-thm">
                <caption>The circumcircle of triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 2.5/4/C}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MAC}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[gray!55](MAB,O MBC,O MAC,O)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[red!60!black](O,A O,B O,C)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](A,MAB,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](B,MBC,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](A,MAC,O)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,A O,B O,C)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[sloped, above](O,A){$R$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above left](A,C){$b$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$a$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$c$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
                The <term>circumradius</term> <m>R</m>, satisfies
                <md>
                    R = \frac{abc}{4 \cdot \Delta}.
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Let <m>\angle ACB = \theta</m>, and label the midpoint of <m>AB</m> as <m>M</m>, so <m>\triangle AMO</m> is a right-angled triangle.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-thm-proof">
                <caption>The circumcircle of triangle <m>ABC</m>.</caption>
                <image width="85%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 2.5/4/C}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MAC}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[gray!55, thin](MAB,O MBC,O MAC,O)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[red!60!black](O,A O,B O,C)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O,MAB)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](A,MAB,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](B,MBC,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](A,MAC,O)
                          \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.4](A,O,MAB)
                          \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.4](A,C,B)
                          \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.6](A,C,B){$\theta$}
                          \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.6](A,O,MAB){$\theta$}
                          \tkzFillAngle[blue!30, opacity=0.5, size=0.4](A,C,B)
                          \tkzFillAngle[blue!30, opacity=0.5, size=0.4](A,O,MAB)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,A O,B O,C)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=||](MAB,A MAB,B)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](MAB){$M$}
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped](O,A){$R$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above left](A,C){$b$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$a$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below, yshift=-20pt](A,B){$c$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](MAB,A){$c/2$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                We have <m>\angle AOB = 2\theta</m> (central angle is twice the inscribed angle), and <m>\angle AOM = \frac{\angle AOB}{2} = \theta</m>, as <m>\triangle AOM</m> and <m>\triangle BOC</m> are congruent (with three equal sides).
            </p>
            <p>
                Moreover, <m>AM = \frac{AB}{2} = \frac{c}{2}</m> since <m>M</m> is a midpoint, and <m>AO = R</m> by definition of the circumradius. Using right-angled trigonometry in <m>\triangle AMO</m> gives:
                <md number="yes" xml:id="eq-circumradius-sine">
                    \sin \theta = \frac{\frac{c}{2}}{R} = \frac{c}{2R}
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                By the formula for the area of <m>\triangle ABC</m> in terms of two sides and the included angle, we have:
                <md>
                    \Delta = \frac{1}{2}ab \sin \theta
                </md>
                Applying <xref ref="eq-circumradius-sine" /> gives:
                <md>
                    <mrow> \Delta = \frac{1}{2}ab \cdot \frac{c}{2R} = \frac{abc}{4R} </mrow>
                    <mrow> R = \frac{abc}{4 \cdot \Delta}. </mrow>
                </md>  
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Comparing the Circumcircle and the Incircle</title>
        <p>
            Every triangle has exactly one circumcircle and exactly one incircle. They are different in construction and location:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>incircle</term> is the largest circle that fits <em>inside</em> the triangle, tangent to all three sides. Its centre (the incenter) is always inside the triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>circumcircle</term> is the unique circle that passes through all three vertices. Its centre (the circumcenter) is inside the triangle only when the triangle is acute.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            For an equilateral triangle, both circles share the same centre and <m>R = 2r</m>; the circumradius is exactly twice the inradius.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>   

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Draw a triangle <m>ABC</m> with <m>AB = 7</m> cm, <m>BC = 5</m> cm, and <m>CA = 6</m> cm. Construct the circumcircle and measure the circumradius. Confirm this by calculation.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="1.">
                    <li>
                        <p>Draw <m>BC = 5</m> cm as a base. Use compasses to mark <m>AB = 7</m> cm from <m>B</m> and <m>CA = 6</m> cm from <m>C</m>; label the intersection <m>A</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Open the compasses to more than half of <m>AB</m>. Place the point at <m>A</m> and draw arcs above and below <m>AB</m>; repeat from <m>B</m>. Join the two arc intersections — this is the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Repeat the construction for side <m>BC</m>. Label the intersection of the two perpendicular bisectors <m>O</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Set the compasses to <m>OA</m> and draw the circumcircle. It should pass through <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Measuring <m>OA</m> from an accurate drawing gives <m>R \approx 3.6</m> cm. We can verify using the formula: with <m>a = 5</m>, <m>b = 6</m>, <m>c = 7</m>, semi-perimeter <m>s = 9</m>, Heron's formula gives
                <md>
                    <mrow>\Delta \amp= \sqrt{9 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2} = \sqrt{216} = 6\sqrt{6} \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>R \amp= \frac{5 \times 6 \times 7}{4 \times 6\sqrt{6}} = \frac{210}{24\sqrt{6}} = \frac{35}{4\sqrt{6}} = \frac{35\sqrt{6}}{24} \approx 3.57 \text{ cm.}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-5-6-7">
                <caption>Triangle with <m>AB=7</m>, <m>BC=5</m>, <m>CA=6</m> and its circumcircle. The perpendicular bisectors of <m>AB</m> and <m>BC</m> meet at circumcenter <m>O</m>.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 7/0/B}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{6}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{5}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                          \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawLines[gray!55, thin, add=0.6 and 0.6](MAB,O MBC,O)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](A,MAB,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](B,MBC,O)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above left](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$7$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$5$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$6$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-right-angle">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>6</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm, and <m>10</m> cm.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Draw the triangle accurately and construct the circumcircle. Where does the circumcenter fall?</li>
                    <li>Find the circumradius by calculation and compare with your measured value.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-6-8-10">
                <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>6</m> cm and <m>8</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>10</m> cm.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 0/8/C}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](B,A,C)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$6$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$8$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$10$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw the right triangle with the right angle at one vertex. Construct the perpendicular bisectors of two sides, they meet at <m>O</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-circum-6-8-10-soln">
                <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>6</m> cm and <m>8</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>10</m> cm. The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 0/8/C}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)
                          \tkzDrawSegment(A,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](B,A,C)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,B O,C O,A)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below left](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$6$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$8$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$10$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
                <p>
                    The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies at the midpoint of the hypotenuse. This is because angles subtended by the diameter of a circle are always right angles (recall <xref ref="sec-angles-subtended-by-the-diameter"/>), so <m>CB</m> is a diameter.
                </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The area of the triangle is <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 6 \times 8 = 24</m> cm<m>^2</m>. Using the general formula for the circumradius:
                        <md>
                            R = \frac{abc}{4 \cdot \Delta} = \frac{6\times 8 \times 10}{4 \times 24} = 5 \text{ cm}
                        </md>
                        This agrees with the measured radius from part (a), and is also half of the hypotenuse, as expected.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In a triangle, side <m>BC = 3\sqrt{3}</m> cm and the circumradius is <m>R = 3</m> cm. Find <m>\theta = \angle BAC</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-to-angle">
                <caption>.</caption>
                <image width="80%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 190 radius 3] \tkzGetPoint{B}
                            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 60 radius 3] \tkzGetPoint{A}
                            \tkzInterCC[R](B,5.19)(O,3) \tkzGetSecondPoint{C}
                            
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[gray](O,B O,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C,O)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.9, fill=orange!25](B,A,C)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.3](B,A,C){$\theta$}
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](C)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above right, sloped](O,B){$3$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$3\sqrt{3}$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Using the same reasoning as in the proof of <xref ref="thm-circumscribed-circle"/>, we have:
                <md>
                    \sin \theta = \frac{BC}{2R} = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2 \cdot 3} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
                </md>
                Thus using exact values, <m>\theta = 60^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each triangle below, use a pair of compasses and a straightedge to construct the <term>circumscribed circle</term> (circumcircle).
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>Acute scalene triangle.</p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.6/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Right triangle (right angle at <m>B</m>).</p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Obtuse triangle.</p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Equilateral triangle.</p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the circumcircle:
                        </p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.6/A}
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{Mb}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](Ma,O Mb,O Mc,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](C,Ma,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](A,Mb,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](B,Mc,O)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,O,Ma,Mb,Mc)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the circumcircle:
                        </p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, 0/3/A}
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](Ma,O Mc,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](C,Ma,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](B,Mc,O)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,O,Ma,Mc)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the circumcircle:
                        </p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 4/0/C, -0.5/2.5/A}
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{Mb}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](Ma,O Mb,O Mc,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](C,Ma,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](A,Mb,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](B,Mc,O)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,O,Ma,Mb,Mc)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above](O){$O$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the circumcircle:
                        </p>
                        <image width="90%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 2.5/4.33/A}
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)\tkzGetPoint{Ma}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(C,A)\tkzGetPoint{Mb}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)\tkzGetPoint{Mc}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](Ma,O Mb,O Mc,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](C,Ma,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](A,Mb,O)
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](B,Mc,O)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,O,Ma,Mb,Mc)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>ABC</m> has <m>AB = 7</m> cm, <m>BC = 8</m> cm, and <m>CA = 6</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle accurately using ruler and compasses.</li>
                        <li>Construct the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>.</li>
                        <li>Construct the perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m>. Label the intersection <m>O</m>.</li>
                        <li>Draw the circumcircle with centre <m>O</m>. Measure the circumradius <m>R</m>.</li>
                        <li>Check your answer: measure <m>OA</m>, <m>OB</m>, and <m>OC</m>. What do you find?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-6-7-8">
                    <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with <m>AB=7</m> cm, <m>BC=8</m> cm, <m>CA=6</m> cm. Construct the circumcircle.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 7/0/B}
                              \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{6}
                              \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{8}
                              \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                              \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                              \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$7$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[right](B,C){$8$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$6$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Here is the construction.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-6-7-8-soln">
                <caption>Triangle with <m>AB=7</m>, <m>BC=8</m>, <m>CA=6</m> and its circumcircle. The perpendicular bisectors of <m>AB</m> and <m>BC</m> meet at circumcenter <m>O</m>.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 7/0/B}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{6}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{8}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                          \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawLines[gray!55, thin, add=0.6 and 0.6](MAB,O MBC,O)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](A,MAB,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](B,MBC,O)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above left](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$7$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$8$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$6$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
                <p>
                    Finding the circumradius <m>R</m>, we have <m>s = \frac{7+8+6}{2} = 10.5</m>,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\Delta \amp= \sqrt{10.5 \times 2.5 \times 4.5 \times 3.5} = \sqrt{413.4375} \approx 20.33 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>R \amp= \frac{6 \times 7 \times 8}{4 \times 20.33} \approx \frac{336}{81.3} \approx 4.13 \text{ cm.}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has sides <m>9</m> cm, <m>12</m> cm, and <m>15</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Copy the triangle accurately and construct the circumcircle. Before you start: predict where the circumcenter will fall. Explain your prediction.</li>
                        <li>Find the circumradius by calculation and check it matches your diagram.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-9-12-15">
                    <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>9</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>15</m> cm.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=30]

                                %% --- SET ---
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B, 0/12/C}
                                %% --- DRAW ---
                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C)

                                %% --- MARK ---
                                \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.35](B,A,C)

                                %% --- LABEL ---
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                                \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$9$}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$12$}
                                \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$15$}
                                \end{scope}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The circumcenter should fall at the midpoint of the hypotenuse (15 cm side). After construction, the circumcenter <m>O</m> should indeed be at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.
                        </p>
                         <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-9-12-15-soln">
                            <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>9</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>15</m> cm. The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.</caption>
                            <image width="60%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
                                    \begin{scope}[rotate=30]
                                    %% --- SET ---
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B, 0/12/C}

                                    %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                                    %% --- DRAW ---
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                                    %% --- MARK ---
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.35](B,A,C)
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,B)(O,C)

                                    %% --- LABEL ---
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[below left](O){$O$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$9$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$12$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$15$}
                                    \end{scope}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            As in <xref ref="ex-right-angle"/>, <m>R = \frac{c}{2} = \frac{15}{2} \,\text{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-pentagon-circumcircles">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Both pentagons below have five equal sides (shown by the tick marks). The first is a <term>regular</term> pentagon — equal sides <em>and</em> equal angles. The second is <term>equilateral but not regular</term>: its sides are equal, but its angles are not.
                </p>
                <sidebyside widths="44% 44%" margins="auto">
                    <figure xml:id="fig-pent-regular-start">
                        <caption>A regular pentagon.</caption>
                        <image width="100%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){Z}\tkzDefShiftPoint[Z](2.5,0){pr}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 90](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V0}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 162](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V1}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 234](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V2}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 306](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V3}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 18](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V4}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](V0,V1 V1,V2 V2,V3 V3,V4 V4,V0)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above](V0){$V_0$}\tkzLabelPoint[left](V1){$V_1$}
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[below left](V2){$V_2$}\tkzLabelPoint[below right](V3){$V_3$}
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[right](V4){$V_4$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-pent-irregular-start">
                        <caption>An equilateral pentagon: equal sides, unequal angles.</caption>
                        <image width="100%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){P0}\tkzDefPoint(3,0){P1}\tkzDefPoint(2.073,2.853){P2}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(-0.499,4.398){P3}\tkzDefPoint(-2.262,1.971){P4}
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](P0,P1,P2,P3,P4)
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](P0,P1 P1,P2 P2,P3 P3,P4 P4,P0)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](P0,P1,P2,P3,P4)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[below left](P0){$P_0$}\tkzLabelPoint[below right](P1){$P_1$}
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[right](P2){$P_2$}\tkzLabelPoint[above right](P3){$P_3$}
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[left](P4){$P_4$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>For the regular pentagon, choose any three vertices and construct the circle that passes through them (the circumcircle of those three points). What do you notice about the remaining two vertices?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Now do the same for the equilateral pentagon: construct the circle through the three vertices <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, <m>P_2</m>. Do the other two vertices, <m>P_3</m> and <m>P_4</m>, lie on it?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>A polygon whose vertices all lie on one circle is called <term>cyclic</term>. Which of the two pentagons is cyclic? What does this tell you about the difference between <em>equilateral</em> (equal sides) and <em>regular</em> (equal sides and equal angles)?</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The circle through any three vertices of the regular pentagon passes through <em>all five</em>. Every vertex is the same distance from the centre <m>O</m>, so they all lie on one circle — the regular pentagon is cyclic, and that circle is its circumcircle.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-pent-regular-soln">
                            <caption>The circle through <m>V_0</m>, <m>V_1</m>, <m>V_2</m> also passes through <m>V_3</m> and <m>V_4</m>.</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0,0){Z}\tkzDefShiftPoint[Z](2.5,0){pr}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 90](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V0}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 162](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 234](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 306](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V3}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 18](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V4}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](V0,V1,V2)\tkzGetPoint{Oc}
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](Oc,V0)
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                        \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](V0,V1 V1,V2 V2,V3 V3,V4 V4,V0)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](V3,V4)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=4pt, red](V0,V1,V2)
                                        \tkzDrawPoint[size=2.5pt](Oc)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[above](V0){$V_0$}\tkzLabelPoint[left](V1){$V_1$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below left](V2){$V_2$}\tkzLabelPoint[below right](V3){$V_3$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](V4){$V_4$}\tkzLabelPoint[below](Oc){$O$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The circle through <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, <m>P_2</m> does <em>not</em> pass through <m>P_3</m> or <m>P_4</m> — they lie outside it. The five vertices of this pentagon do not all lie on any single circle.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-pent-irregular-soln">
                            <caption>The circle through <m>P_0</m>, <m>P_1</m>, <m>P_2</m> misses <m>P_3</m> and <m>P_4</m> (orange).</caption>
                            <image width="48%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0,0){P0}\tkzDefPoint(3,0){P1}\tkzDefPoint(2.073,2.853){P2}
                                        \tkzDefPoint(-0.499,4.398){P3}\tkzDefPoint(-2.262,1.971){P4}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](P0,P1,P2)\tkzGetPoint{Oc}
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](Oc,P0)
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](P0,P1,P2,P3,P4)
                                        \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](P0,P1 P1,P2 P2,P3 P3,P4 P4,P0)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=4pt, red](P0,P1,P2)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=4pt, orange!80!black](P3,P4)
                                        \tkzDrawPoint[size=2.5pt](Oc)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below left](P0){$P_0$}\tkzLabelPoint[below right](P1){$P_1$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](P2){$P_2$}\tkzLabelPoint[above right](P3){$P_3$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[left](P4){$P_4$}\tkzLabelPoint[below](Oc){$O$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Only the regular pentagon is cyclic. Equal sides on their own are not enough — an equilateral polygon need not have its vertices on a common circle. The vertices lie on one circumcircle only when the polygon is <em>regular</em>, that is, equal sides <em>and</em> equal angles. So <q>equilateral</q> is a weaker condition than <q>regular</q>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A fragment of a broken circular grinding wheel survives as a single curved arc, shown below — its centre is missing. A fundi wants to recover the original circle so that he can cut a replacement.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-recover-arc">
                    <caption>The surviving arc of the wheel, with three chosen points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>S</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefShiftPoint[O](4,0){r0}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 40](r0)\tkzGetPoint{Aen}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 140](r0)\tkzGetPoint{Ast}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 125](r0)\tkzGetPoint{P}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 90](r0)\tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 55](r0)\tkzGetPoint{S}
                                \tkzDrawArc[brown, line width=1.3pt](O,Aen)(Ast)
                                \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](P,Q,S)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](S)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Using compasses and a straightedge, construct the perpendicular bisectors of the chords <m>PQ</m> and <m>QS</m>. Explain why their intersection <m>O</m> is the centre of the original circle.</li>
                        <li>With centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>OP</m>, draw the complete circle. It should pass through all three points.</li>
                        <li>Why does the method give the same centre no matter which three points of the arc are chosen?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Every point on the perpendicular bisector of a chord is equidistant from the chord's two endpoints. So the perpendicular bisector of <m>PQ</m> consists of the points equidistant from <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, and the perpendicular bisector of <m>QS</m> the points equidistant from <m>Q</m> and <m>S</m>. Their intersection <m>O</m> is therefore equidistant from all three: <m>OP = OQ = OS</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>OP = OQ = OS</m>, the circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>OP</m> passes through <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>S</m> — it is the original wheel (the circumcircle of triangle <m>PQS</m>).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Drawing the circle:
                            </p>
                             <figure xml:id="fig-circum-recover-soln">
                                <caption>The perpendicular bisectors of <m>PQ</m> (red) and <m>QS</m> (blue) meet at the centre <m>O</m>; the recovered circle (dashed) passes through all three points.</caption>
                                <image width="55%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                            %% --- SET ---
                                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                            \tkzDefShiftPoint[O](4,0){r0}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 40](r0)\tkzGetPoint{Aen}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 140](r0)\tkzGetPoint{Ast}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 125](r0)\tkzGetPoint{P}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 90](r0)\tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                            \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center O angle 55](r0)\tkzGetPoint{S}
                                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                            \tkzDefMidPoint(P,Q)\tkzGetPoint{Mpq}
                                            \tkzDefMidPoint(Q,S)\tkzGetPoint{Mqs}
                                            %% --- DRAW ---
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[gray](O,r0)
                                            \tkzDrawArc[brown, line width=1.3pt](O,Aen)(Ast)
                                            \tkzDrawSegments[thin](P,Q Q,S)
                                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.3 and 1.3, red](Mpq,O)
                                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.3 and 1.3, blue](Mqs,O)
                                            %% --- MARK ---
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.22](P,Mpq,O)
                                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.22](Q,Mqs,O)
                                            %% --- LABEL ---
                                            \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](P,Q,S,O)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](P)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](S)
                                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](O){$O$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Any three distinct points of the arc are three points of the same circle, and a circle is completely determined by three of its points. So the construction recovers the same centre and radius whichever three points are chosen.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In triangle <m>ABC</m>, <m>BC = \sqrt{18}</m> cm and the circumradius is <m>3</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>By drawing a diagram, find angle <m>BAC</m>.</li>
                        <li>On your diagram, construct another possible triangle <m>ABC</m> with the same circumradius and side length <m>BC</m>, but different lengths for the other sides.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Drawing the triangle and circumcircle:
                        </p>
                        <image width="80%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                    %% --- SET ---
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 160 radius 3] \tkzGetPoint{B}
                                    \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 40 radius 3] \tkzGetPoint{A}
                                    \tkzInterCC[R](B,4.24)(O,3) \tkzGetSecondPoint{C}

                                    %% --- DRAW ---
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[gray](O,B O,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C,O)
                                    %% --- MARK ---
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.9, fill=orange!25](B,A,C)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.3](B,A,C){$\alpha$}
                                    %% --- LABEL ---
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above right](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[above](O,B){$3$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,C){$\sqrt{18}$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        <p>
                            Using the same reasoning as in the proof of <xref ref="thm-circumscribed-circle"/>, we have:
                            <md>
                                \sin \alpha = \frac{BC}{2R} = \frac{\sqrt{18}}{2 \cdot 3} = \frac{3\sqrt{2}}{6} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}.
                            </md>
                            Thus using exact values, <m>\alpha = 45^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Any other point <m>A'</m> on the circumcircle will give a triangle with the same circumradius and side length <m>BC</m>, but different lengths for the other sides, for example:
                        </p>
                        <image width="80%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                    %% --- SET ---
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 160 radius 3] \tkzGetPoint{B}
                                    \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 60 radius 3] \tkzGetPoint{A}
                                    \tkzInterCC[R](B,4.24)(O,3) \tkzGetSecondPoint{C}

                                    %% --- DRAW ---
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[gray](O,B O,C)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C,O)
                                    %% --- MARK ---
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.9, fill=orange!25](B,A,C)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.3](B,A,C){$45^\circ$}
                                    %% --- LABEL ---
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above right](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[left](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above](O){$O$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[above](O,B){$3$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,C){$\sqrt{18}$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An equilateral triangle has side length <m>12</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle and construct both its circumcircle and its incircle. What do you notice about their centres?</li>
                        <li>Calculate the circumradius <m>R</m> and inradius <m>r</m>.</li>
                        <li>Show that <m>R = 2r</m>. How does this match what you see in your diagram?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For an equilateral triangle, the angle bisectors and perpendicular bisectors all coincide, so the incenter and circumcenter are the same point.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-equilateral">
                            <caption>Equilateral triangle with side <m>12</m> cm, circumcircle (blue) and incircle (orange). For an equilateral triangle the circumcenter and incenter coincide.</caption>
                            <image width="55%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]

                                    %% --- SET ---
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 12/0/B}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center A angle 60](B)  \tkzGetPoint{C}

                                    %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoints{I}{Ix}

                                    %% --- DRAW ---
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[orange!80!black, thick](I,Ix)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                                    %% --- MARK ---
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](A,B B,C A,C)

                                    %% --- LABEL ---
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$12$}

                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Finding the area, with semi-perimeter <m>s = \frac{12+12+12}{2} = 18</m> cm,
                            <md> 
                                <mrow> \Delta \amp = \sqrt{18 \times (18-12) \times (18-12) \times (18-12)} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{2\times3^2 \times 6^3} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = 18\sqrt{2\times 6} =  36\sqrt{3} \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Finding the circumradius:
                            <md> R = \frac{abc}{4 \cdot \Delta} = \dfrac{12^3}{4 \times 36\sqrt{3}} = \dfrac{12}{\sqrt{3}} = 4\sqrt{3}</md>
                            Finding the inradius:
                            <md>
                                r = \frac{\Delta}{s} = \frac{36\sqrt{3}}{18} = 2 \sqrt{3}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>R = 4\sqrt{3} = 2 \times 2\sqrt{3} = 2r</m>. <m>\checkmark</m> In the diagram, the circumcircle's radius is visibly twice the incircle's radius:
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-equilateral-2r">
                            <caption>Equilateral triangle with side <m>12</m> cm, circumcircle (blue) and incircle (orange). For an equilateral triangle the circumcenter and incenter coincide.</caption>
                            <image width="55%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]

                                    %% --- SET ---
                                    \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 12/0/B}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center A angle 60](B)  \tkzGetPoint{C}

                                    %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                    \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[reflection = over C--A](O) \tkzGetPoint{K}
                                    \tkzDefMidPoint(K,O)\tkzGetPoint{M}
                                    \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoints{I}{Ix}

                                    %% --- DRAW ---
                                    \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[orange!80!black, thick](I,Ix)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O, I, M)

                                    %% --- MARK ---
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,M M,K)
                                    \tkzDrawSegment(O,K)

                                    %% --- LABEL ---
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$12$}

                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-euler-line">
    <statement>
        <p>
            A triangle has vertices <m>A(1,5)</m>, <m>B(0,0)</m>, and <m>C(7,0)</m>. You will locate three of its centres and discover a famous relationship between them. (Find <m>O</m> simply as the point equidistant from the three vertices.)
        </p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li><p>Find the coordinates of the <term>centroid</term> <m>G</m> (the average of the three vertices).</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the <term>orthocentre</term> <m>H</m>, where the three altitudes meet. (The altitude from <m>A</m> is vertical; the altitude from <m>B</m> is perpendicular to <m>AC</m>.)</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the <term>circumcentre</term> <m>O</m>, the point equidistant from <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Plot <m>G</m>, <m>H</m>, and <m>O</m>. What do you notice? Show that <m>HG = 2\,GO</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li><p><m>G = \left(\dfrac{1+0+7}{3},\ \dfrac{5+0+0}{3}\right) = \left(\dfrac{8}{3},\ \dfrac{5}{3}\right)</m>.</p></li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The altitude from <m>A</m> is the vertical line <m>x = 1</m>. Side <m>AC</m> has gradient <m>\dfrac{0-5}{7-1} = -\dfrac{5}{6}</m>, so the altitude from <m>B</m> (perpendicular to <m>AC</m>, through the origin) is <m>y = \dfrac{6}{5}x</m>. At <m>x = 1</m>, <m>y = \dfrac{6}{5}</m>, so <m>H = \left(1,\ \dfrac{6}{5}\right)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m> is <m>x = 3.5</m>; the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m> passes through <m>(0.5,\,2.5)</m> with gradient <m>-\dfrac{1}{5}</m>, giving <m>y = 2.5 - \dfrac{1}{5}(3) = 1.9</m> at <m>x = 3.5</m>. So <m>O = (3.5,\ 1.9)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The three points lie on a single straight line — the <term>Euler line</term>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\vec{HG} \amp = G - H = \left(\tfrac{8}{3}-1,\ \tfrac{5}{3}-\tfrac{6}{5}\right) = \left(\tfrac{5}{3},\ \tfrac{7}{15}\right),</mrow>
                            <mrow>\vec{GO} \amp = O - G = \left(\tfrac{7}{2}-\tfrac{8}{3},\ \tfrac{19}{10}-\tfrac{5}{3}\right) = \left(\tfrac{5}{6},\ \tfrac{7}{30}\right).</mrow>
                        </md>
                        Since <m>\vec{HG} = 2\,\vec{GO}</m>, the points are collinear and <m>HG = 2\,GO</m>: the centroid divides the segment from the orthocentre to the circumcentre in the ratio <m>2:1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-euler-line-soln">
            <caption>The orthocentre <m>H</m>, centroid <m>G</m>, and circumcentre <m>O</m> lie on the Euler line, with <m>HG = 2\,GO</m> (three equal steps).</caption>
            <image width="62%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
                        %% --- SET ---
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 7/0/C, 1/5/A}
                        %% --- CALCULATE: centres ---
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{O}
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[centroid](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{G}
                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[ortho](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{H}
                        \tkzDefMidPoint(G,H)\tkzGetPoint{Mid}
                        %% --- DRAW ---
                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                        \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5, violet, thick, densely dashed](H,O)
                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](A,B,C)
                        \tkzDrawPoint[red,size=4pt](H)
                        \tkzDrawPoint[blue,size=4pt](G)
                        \tkzDrawPoint[teal!60!black,size=4pt](O)
                        %% --- MARK ---
                        \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|, violet](H,Mid Mid,G G,O)
                        %% --- LABEL ---
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                        \tkzLabelPoint[above left, red](H){$H$}
                        \tkzLabelPoint[below, blue](G){$G$}
                        \tkzLabelPoint[above right, teal!60!black](O){$O$}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </solution>
</exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-reuleaux-polygons">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A shape has <term>constant width</term> if, when held between two parallel rulers, the gap between the rulers is the same whichever way you turn the shape. A circle obviously does this — but it is not the only shape that does.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Reuleaux triangle.</alert> Start from the equilateral triangle <m>ABC</m> below. For each vertex in turn, put the compass point on that vertex, open it to the side length, and draw the arc joining the other two vertices. Draw all three arcs.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-reuleaux-tri-start">
                            <caption>An equilateral triangle <m>ABC</m> to build on.</caption>
                            <image width="42%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0,0){B}\tkzDefPoint(4,0){C}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center B angle 60](C)\tkzGetPoint{A}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why your Reuleaux triangle has the same width in every direction, and state that width in terms of the side length <m>s</m>. (Hint: when you trap the shape between two parallel rulers, one ruler touches a vertex and the other touches the arc opposite it.)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Reuleaux pentagon.</alert> Now start from the regular pentagon <m>V_0V_1V_2V_3V_4</m> below. Each side is replaced by an arc centred at the <em>opposite</em> vertex (the one not touching that side), with the compass opened to the long diagonal. Draw the five arcs.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-reuleaux-pent-start">
                            <caption>A regular pentagon <m>V_0V_1V_2V_3V_4</m> to build on.</caption>
                            <image width="42%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0,0){Z}\tkzDefShiftPoint[Z](2.4,0){pr}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 90](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V0}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 162](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 234](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 306](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V3}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 18](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V4}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[above](V0){$V_0$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[left](V1){$V_1$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below left](V2){$V_2$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below right](V3){$V_3$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](V4){$V_4$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The British <m>50</m>p coin is a Reuleaux <em>heptagon</em> — the same idea built on a regular seven-sided polygon. Give one practical reason a coin is made with constant width rather than as an ordinary seven-sided polygon.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Each arc is centred at one vertex and has radius equal to the side length <m>s</m>, joining the other two vertices. The three arcs together form the rounded triangle below.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-reuleaux-tri-soln">
                            <caption>The Reuleaux triangle: each side of the equilateral triangle is replaced by an arc centred at the opposite vertex.</caption>
                            <image width="42%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0,0){B}\tkzDefPoint(4,0){C}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center B angle 60](C)\tkzGetPoint{A}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[gray, thin, densely dashed](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, teal](A,B)(C)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, teal](B,C)(A)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, teal](C,A)(B)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Hold the shape between two parallel rulers. In any direction, one ruler rests against a vertex (say <m>A</m>) and the other rests against the arc opposite <m>A</m>. That arc is centred at <m>A</m> with radius <m>s</m>, so the distance between the two rulers is exactly <m>s</m>. Since this is true for every direction, the width is constant and equal to <m>s</m> — the shape rolls just like a circle of diameter <m>s</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Each side of the pentagon is replaced by an arc centred at the opposite vertex, with radius equal to the long diagonal. The five arcs form the constant-width pentagon below.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-reuleaux-pent-soln">
                            <caption>The Reuleaux pentagon — the shape of the British <m>50</m>p and <m>20</m>p coins is the seven-sided version of this.</caption>
                            <image width="44%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoint(0,0){Z}\tkzDefShiftPoint[Z](2.4,0){pr}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 90](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V0}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 162](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 234](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 306](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V3}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center Z angle 18](pr)\tkzGetPoint{V4}
                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[gray, thin, densely dashed](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, violet](V3,V0)(V1)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, violet](V4,V1)(V2)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, violet](V0,V2)(V3)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, violet](V1,V3)(V4)
                                        \tkzDrawArc[thick, violet](V2,V4)(V0)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](V0,V1,V2,V3,V4)
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[above](V0){$V_0$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[left](V1){$V_1$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below left](V2){$V_2$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below right](V3){$V_3$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](V4){$V_4$}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Because the coin has constant width, a slot or vending machine measures the same width no matter which way the coin is inserted, so it can size and accept it reliably; it also rolls smoothly. At the same time the non-circular shape is easy to tell apart from round coins by touch. (A plain seven-sided polygon would not have constant width, so its measured size would change with orientation.)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>
